{
  "texts": [
    "For each strategy, we aligned each query dataset to the reference dataset and transferred cell-type labels through the k-nearest neighbors (kNN) algorithm, where the ground truth cell-type labels were taken from the trimodal PBMC atlas annotated by MIDAS.",
    "Visualization of the mapped biological states showed that reciprocal reference mapping with different query datasets yielded consistent results, with strong agreement with the atlas integration results obtained with the dogma-full dataset (Fig. 5d and Supplementary Fig.",
    "Micro F1 scores indicated that reciprocal reference mapping outperformed the query-to-reference and reference-to-query mapping strategies for various forms of query data, achieving robust and accurate label transfer and thereby avoiding the need for de novo integration and downstream analysis (Fig. 5e).Thus, MIDAS can be used to transfer atlas-level knowledge to various forms of users' datasets without expensive de novo training or complex downstream analysis.",
    "Application of MIDAS on BMMC mosaic dataTo investigate the application of MIDAS in single-cell datasets with continuous cell state changes, we constructed a human BMMC mosaic dataset, denoted 'bm', by combining three distinct batches (ICA, ASAP and CITE) obtained from publicly available scRNA-seq, ASAP-seq and CITE-seq datasets, respectively (Methods).",
    "The results of de novo integration on bm showed that MIDAS accurately aligned different modalities and removed batch effects while preserving cell-type information (Supplementary Fig. 25a)."
  ]
}